From: markline@waldorf.cc.wwu.edu (Mark Line)
Subject: Re: Linux Consortium
Date: 6 Dec 93 04:29:44 GMT

chris@thoday.demon.co.uk (EurIng Chris Thoday) writes:

>In a previous article I wrote:

>>>>I would like to suggest that the review group should:
>>
>>>>   a) Collect reports from anybody who wishes to report a problem.
>>>>   b) Attempt to verify the problem reports where possible.
>>>>   c) Maintain a database of solutions.
>>>>   d) Issue guidance to distributors.

>In article <1993Dec5.024236.25805@henson.cc.wwu.edu>
>           markline@henson.cc.wwu.edu "Mark Line" replied:

>>I always thought that was what software *developers* are supposed to
>>do. Have I missed something?

>IMHO the answer is certainly "yes". I suspect you have never tried to
>install Linux from a CD-ROM.  I installed the pl7 Yggdrasil CD some time
>ago when I did not have access to the Net. There were quite a few problems
>but I was able to get round them or put up with the things that did not
>work. I was particulary interested in an affordable system that I could
>use to develop X Windows applications on my PC at home.

I misunderstood your reference in that case. You're differentiating
problems with underlying software from the packaging -- I agree with
that approach. So my response to you would then be, "I always thought
that was what software *distributors* are supposed to do. Have I
missed something?" In fact, this makes my argument even stronger. The
developers we're talking about here are working for peanuts, in effect
contributing their time, probably in almost all cases. Distributors,
on the other hand, are charging the consumer *REAL MONEY* for their
product. I can't see the LC or Review Board or whatever you want to
call it doing this work for the distributors, and for free to boot.

BTW -- I have installed from CD-ROM; the only way I ever *have*
installed. Have never had any kind of problem with installation. But
then, it wasn't Yggdrasil -- maybe that's the difference. I'm glad I
was able to *GUESS* correctly at which CD to buy; I certainly couldn't
get any help from anybody else within reasonable bandwidth.

[gory details of abortive installation attempts deleted]

>I suggest that this experience supports the proposals which I quoted
>at the start of this article. I think that the "Linux Consortium",
>or whatever it is called, is badly needed -- and not just for novices.

True. But as I mentioned, I don't see the LC as free personnel for
distributors who are actually getting paid for their efforts,
relatively speaking.

-- Mark

