From: crh@regent.e-technik.tu-muenchen.de (Christian Huebner)
Subject: Re: mounting Panasonic 563B CDROM
Date: 6 Dec 1993 07:46:11 +0100

itd2b@poe.acc.Virginia.EDU (Ingo Tobias Duckerschein) writes:

>I have installed the patch panasonic-563Bcdrom.patch to the kernel
>source in order to use my CDROM drive.  I have compiled the kernel,
>taking care to choose CONFIG_ISO9660_FS, CONFIG_PANASONIC_WHATNOT,
>and CONFIG_SOUND.  Upon boot, the kernel reports that the soundcard
>is detected; however, no CDROM drives are reported as detected.

I use a Panasonic 562 and have no problems with the patch from
Eberhard Moenkeberg (thanks, Eberhard!). Is this the same one You are
using? 

Anyway, my CD-ROM is reported correctly upon boot-up. Yours should
be, too. Have You correctly created the device /dev/mcd0 ?

>I attempt to use the command "mount -t iso9660 /dev/mcd0 /cd0"
>but that returns "mount: wrong fs type, /dev/mcd0 already mounted, 
>/cd0 busy, or other error".  I have also tried using "msdos" as a 
>filesystem (as it is an msdos cd).  This did not work either.

Try creating  '/cd0' if You did not already do so.  The MS/DOS-FS won/t
be of any use to You, as the CD doesn't feature a MS/DOS-FS. It's an 
ISO-9660 FS, which needs a driver for dos also.

>I am not entirely sure /dev/mcd0 is the correct device; if it is not,
>what is?

You have to create Your own device (which may or may not be named mcd0.
It must reside in /dev, though. Read the docs that came with Your 
patch and create the device according to it.

>Also, how do I know if the kernel knows my CDROM drive even
>exists?  The patch applied w/out any rejections, and I have the exact
>model the author reported he used with the patches.

If the kernel knows about Your drive, it will say so on bootup. 
Double-check everything You did with the patch. Read the docs for the
patch. Sorry to sound like a teacher, but there are some real important 
hints in it. (I also have the tendency to ignore docs at first and
to consult them only if nothing works.)

Bye...

Chris
