From: wpp@marie.physik.tu-berlin.de (Kai Petzke)
Subject: Re: [Q] crypt - for non-americans
Date: 6 Dec 1993 10:40:43 GMT

In <2duesf$ddl@belfort.daimi.aau.dk> tange@daimi.aau.dk (Ole Tange) writes:

>I have seen several places that crypt is not to be exported outside 
>USA. Is there a GNU-crypt for us non-americans?

Crypt uses very old algorythms.  The first electronical computer,
build in Britain and operated on valves, was used to crack the
cipher produced by the German Enigma during World War II.  crypt
uses the same algorythm.  Using crypt is like telling to everybody
experienced with cryptoanalysis: "Well, here is something of
importance, please read it."

Use PGP instead.  Its main use is encrypting e-mail, but it can be
used to do plain encryption as well.  There are several non-US
archives of it around, I think, one is nic.funet.fi.

>Please email - this group expires much too fast (don't they all? ;-)

Talk to your newsadmin.  Very likely, they is missing disk space to
keep them longer.

--
Kai
wpp@marie.physik.tu-berlin.de
Advertisement by Microsoft in a well-known German magazine:
        If you don't like our programmes, than make your own ones.
However, they expect you to use Microsoft products for this -:)

